<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government: Peace Not Jeopardized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government: Peace Not Jeopardized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1604000894 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2236 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1604000894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez, Chiapas, 15 Apr (DPA) -- The 
Mexican Government has said that today's predawn attack on a 
military checkpoint in southern Chiapas does not jeopardize the 
peace process in this strife-torn region that borders Guatemala. 
  A spokesman for the Mexican presidential palace told DPA 
there does not seem to be any relation between the attack on the 
checkpoint near Tuxtla Gutierrez and the armed conflict that 
broke out in this state on 1 January. In this way, the 
government dismissed reports that the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army (EZLN), which took up arms on New Year's Day, 
waged the attack. 
  Chiapas Attorney General Arturo Becerra said that so far 
there are no indications the EZLN was involved in the attack on 
the checkpoint located on the highway leading from Tuxtla 
Gutierrez to Chicoasen, a town that is far removed from the 
guerrilla's zone of operations. 
  Chiapas Governor Javier Lopez Moreno, in turn, stressed that 
the truce between the insurgents and the Mexican Army, which has 
been in effect since 12 January when the government ordered a 
unilateral cease-fire of its offensive actions, "is alive." 
  The Defense Secretariat today said an Army sergeant died as 
a 
result of wounds sustained when "a small group of unidentified 
civilians" opened fire on the military checkpoint. According to 
the official report, the Army repelled the "armed assault" and 
the assailants fled. It is believed that they are hidden in 
caves in the mountains near the site of the skirmish. There is 
no word on casualties among the attackers. 
  An hour afer the clash, which began at approximately 0530 
(1130 GMT), several Armed Forces helicopter gunships were still 
flying over the area and firing, according to reports from 
residents. The area was reopened to traffic after it had been 
sealed off for several hours. 
  The EZLN recently charged that the Army has been mobilizing 
troops and warned that such deployments threaten the peace 
process, which began on 21 February. The first phase of the 
peace process ended on 2 March when the government announced its 
responses to a 34-point list of demands submitted by the rebels. 
  In the wake of the murder of Luis Donaldo Colosio, the 
ruling 
party's presidential candidate, the EZLN suspended its 
consultations on the government's proposals -- consultations 
that were being held within Indian villages located in the 
EZLN's area of influence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

