<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN Denies Involvement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EZLN Denies Involvement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1604191594 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1814 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1604191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 16 Apr (EFE) -- The Zapatista National 
Liberation Army [EZLN] said it has no involvement in the attack 
on an Army post, which took place in Tuxtla Gutierrez, Chiapas 
State, in southeastern Mexico, on Friday. In a communique sent 
to the media, EZLN leader "Subcommander Marcos" indicated that 
the EZLN has no military position at all or troops in the area 
where the attack took place. 
  Unidentified persons early Friday morning attacked an Army 
post in the town of Chicoasen, some 8 km from the Chiapas State 
capital, in which a sergeant was killed. "The EZLN does not 
have good weapons or sufficient vehicles, but it does have 
military honor and its word; the EZLN promised, if it is not 
attacked, not to carry out offensive military operations against 
federal troops or their positions," the communique stated. 
  The rebel group reiterated its commitment to respect the 
cease-fire and promised not to carry out offensive military 
actions against government forces in the entire national 
territory under the conditions set forth on 12 January when the 
truce was accepted. Marcos reiterated the guerrillas' commitment 
to continue working for a dialogue in search of peace with 
justice and dignity. He added that the EZLN is waiting for the 
reestablishment of the proper conditions to resume the dialogue 
with the government. 
  The EZLN rose up in arms on 1 January to demand social 
justice for the Indians, and their clashes with the government 
forces lasted until 12 January, when a cease-fire was decreed by 
both sides. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

