<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Menem Admits Corrupt Government Officials Exist </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Menem Admits Corrupt Government Officials Exist </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1504213894 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2251 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1504213894 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 14 Apr (EFE) -- Argentine President 
Carlos Menem today admitted that, in his administration, "there 
still are officials who commit acts of corruption" and people 
who, "through bribes, instigate the corruption of government 
officials." 
  In remarks to Radio La Red of Buenos Aires, Menem added: "We 
have done away with a system in which corruption had been 
established for many years, that is, the oversized state that we 
had. There were state-owned enterprises that had truly become 
centers of corruption." 
  Menem emphasized that his government "had dismantled this 
system" and asked entrepreneurs to cooperate and "help in 
eliminating these small centers." 
  The reports on alleged acts of corruption within the 
retirees 
social services organization (PAMI) [Comprehensive Medical 
Assistance Plan] has been described by political observers as 
one of the reasons why the ruling Justicialist Party (PJ, 
Peronist) lost in the country's capital the Constituent Assembly 
elections held on 10 April. 
  PAMI President Matilde Menendez, the No. 2 candidate on the 
PJ ticket for these elections, resigned as a Constituent 
Assembly member 48 hours after the elections, but denied that 
she was involved in acts of corruption and asked the General 
Directorate of Taxation (DGI) to investigate her assets. 

</TEXT>

