<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Paz Zamora's Congressional Testimony </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Paz Zamora's Congressional Testimony </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1504182294 La Paz Television Nacional Network in Spanish 
0300 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1504182294 </F>
<F P=104>  La Paz Television Nacional Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Here are the highlights of former President 
Jaime Paz Zamora's six-hour testimony before the Constituent 
Commission. 
  [Begin recording] [Amalia Pando] In his testimony before the 
Constituent Commission, former President Jaime Paz Zamora 
declared he was both a victim of his own mistakes as well as 
those of the Special Antinarcotics Force [FELCN] and the 
Prosecutor's office. 
  He referred to a U.S. plot that is allegedly focusing on him 
because his government defended coca farming at an international 
level and because he invited Fidel Castro to visit Bolivia. 
  [Paz] I hope the commission agrees with me when I say that 
we 
run the risk of our ineffective struggle against drug 
trafficking being used within our country for political or other 
purposes. [passage omitted] 
  Do you not think, when I saw the regrettable way in which 
the 
FELCN and the Prosecutor General acted, I did not wonder how 
they acted in previous cases and how many people may have been 
victims of this irresponsible, corrupt, and superficial 
management of our prisons throughout the country. 
  [Pando] During his administration, Paz Zamora was asked to 
safeguard our sovereignty in light of the obvious intervention 
by the U.S. Embassy. At that time Paz Zamora talked about a 
sham [pacotilla] sovereignty. 
  [Paz] We must not let the FELCN, in the name of the noble 
struggle against drug trafficking, become a nightmare for the 
citizenry as was the case of the Tonton Macoutes in Haiti. 
  [Pando] The former president then made a series of charges 
which had been reported by the media throughout the four years 
of his administration. 
  [Paz] Higher ranking FELCN officers, district prosecutors, 
and the special prosecutors for drug cases receive their 
salaries directly from the financial cooperation granted by the 
United States. This is not normal. I would say this is a 
typical case of cooperation -- which we need -- but which could 
turn into intervention. After all, you obey the one who pays 
you your salary. 
  [Pando] He ended his attacks against the FELCN and the 
prosecutors in a categorical manner. 
  [Paz] Nothing of what was said was true. [passage omitted] 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

