<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investment To Replace Debt Conversion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Investment To Replace Debt Conversion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1504204594 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 15 Apr 94 
p 19 </F>

<F P=103> PY1504204594 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- A result of the foreign debt agreement, 
debt conversion will again be replaced by direct investments in 
the country, which were suspended in 1987. This mechanism 
allows foreign banks to immediately receive real cruzeiros to 
invest in Brazil, instead of having to wait to receive payment 
in foreign currency. The Central Bank believes that the country 
will immediately obtain $210 million for the capitalization of 
financial institutions or holdings, whether or not these 
institutions have foreign capital. 
  According to the provision promulgated yesterday by the 
Central Bank, creditors who in 1998 lent fresh money to Brazil 
have two options: exchange the money which has not been used, 
and is still deposited at the Central Bank, for new certificates 
for the rescheduled debt; or invest in the capitalization of 
companies in the country. The Central bank provision demands, 
however, that these creditors have a balance in the PFA 
(Parallel Financing Accord) [Acordo Paralelo de Financimaneto], 
which was one of the four types of fresh money used in 1987. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

