<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Electoral Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1604191294 </F>
<F P=103> PA1604191294 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the run-off in the Salvadoran 
presidential elections scheduled for 24 April 1994. 
  Armando Calderon Sol and Enrique Borgo Bustamente, 
presidential and vice presidential candidates, respectively, for 
the Nationalist Republican Alliance, ARENA, campaigned over the 
past weekend in Sonsonate, Santa Ana, San Vicente, and 
Sensuntepeque. In Sonsonate Calderon Sol said that he wants to 
win the run-off elections convincingly. He stated that "the 
people must categorically show their disagreement with leftist 
ideas." The candidate pointed out that he will continue to 
develop the national reconstruction strategy and work for the 
establishment of a state of law to generate trust in and respect 
for the country's legal system. Calderon Sol praised the 
"political maturity" of parties that will not be in the run-off 
elections, but will support ARENA. Meanwhile, Borgo Bustamente 
said that ARENA did not win the elections in the first round due 
to "a legal technicality," and not because of lack of voter 
support. (San Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA in Spanish 11 Apr 94 p 
5) 
  Ruben Zamora, presidential candidate for the Farabundo Marti 
National Liberation Front-Democratic Convergence Coalition, met 
over the past weekend with groups that pledged support to his 
coalition in the run-off elections. He held meetings in the 
Municipalities of Ciudad Delgado, Mejicanos, Apopa, Ilopango, 
and Soyapango, in San Salvador Department. Zamora added that he 
has met with leaders of the Christian Democratic Party and Unity 
Movement, but those parties decided to let their members vote 
for whomever they wish. The candidate denied that fellow party 
members voiced support for ARENA publicly, quite the contrary, 
the coalition has identified "a natural increase in the number 
of followers coming from parties that oppose ARENA." Zamora and 
his vice presidential candidate Francisco Lima will make public 
appearances next weekend in Santa Ana, San Salvador, Santa 
Tecla, and San Miguel to close their campaign. (San Salvador LA 
PRENSA GRAFICA in Spanish 11 Apr 94 p 5) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

