<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft of National Antidrug Control Plan Disclosed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Draft of National Antidrug Control Plan Disclosed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1504232894 Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 3 Apr 94 pp A14-A15 </F>
<F P=103> PY1504232894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EXPRESO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Liz Mineo] </F>
  [Text] The creation of the National System for the Control 
and Repression of Drug Production and Drug Trafficking [Sistema 
Nacional de Control y Represion de la Produccion y el Trafico 
Ilicito de Drogas] is the most important contribution 
encompassed in the national antidrug plan drafted by a 
commission of experts at the government's request. 
  According to the draft, this new drug control system will 
group all the many dispersed antidrug government actions which 
need to be centralized and organized. 
  The new Peruvian Government antidrug policy organization 
will 
fulfill functions similar to the Office of National Drug Control 
Policy, which drafts, centralizes, and implements the U.S. 
Government's antidrug strategy under the leadership of Drug Czar 
Lee Brown. 
  The influence of the U.S. model does not stop there, because 
the National Drug Control and Drug Prevention Plan [Plan 
Nacional de Prevencion y Control de Drogas] -- which is already 
in President Alberto Fujimori's hands for study and approval -- 
is a Peruvian version of U.S. goals, objectives, plans, and 
programs in this area. 
  The Peruvian program encompasses drug production and drug 
trafficking; alternative development programs; and drug 
prevention, treatment, and rehabilitation. 
  The plans call for the national system to be divided into 
four subsystems, each of which will concentrate their efforts on 
drug control and drug repression activities in the battle 
against drugs; the deviation of chemical precursors and inputs; 
the transfer of funds and laundered money; drug production and 
drug trafficking; and the smuggling of arms and explosives. 
  These subsystems will be subordinated to the central 
organization, which will be in charge of the planning, 
coordinating, controlling, and information and decisionmaking 
process of the antidrug efforts to be undertaken by the Peruvian 
Government from 1994 to the year 2000. 
  In addition to creating this arm for the antidrug struggle, 
the plan has 20 other objectives, among which are the 
development of the alternative development program, the 
monitoring of coca crops, the safeguarding of the environment, 
and the development of research programs for the beneficial use 
of coca. 
  The main objectives are centered on the gradual reduction of 
coca crops, the repression of drug production and drug 
trafficking, and decreased drug use. 
  By the year 2000 the goal of this ambitious project is to 
incorporate through the alternative development programs at 
least 50 percent of the peasant population currently involved in 
coca production for illegal purposes in legal farming activities. 
  In addition to alternative development, the plan proposes a 
strategy based on the establishment of legal and institutional 
order. 
  According to the draft, during the 1994-2000 period the 
promotion of the alternative development program will be granted 
"top priority" with the objective of achieving the reduction of 
coca crops used for illegal purposes. 
  The national antidrug plan, the first of its kind in our 
country, was drafted by a multisectorial commission headed by 
General Arnaldo Velarde Ramirez, Peruvian representative to the 
OAS Inter-American Committee for the Control of Drugs and Drug 
Abuse (CICAD). 
  The commission was established in November, and is made up 
of 
representatives from government ministries, with support from 
the United Nations International Drug Control Program [Programa 
de las Naciones Unidas para la Fiscalizacion Internacional de 
Drogas] (PNUFID) and prominent experts on the matter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10748 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat074_r_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ineffectiveness of Antidrug Plan Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ineffectiveness of Antidrug Plan Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1504190694 Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p A8 </F>
<F P=103> PY1504190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EXPRESO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Liz Mineo] </F>
  [Text] Since February 1978, when the government promulgated 
the first national antinarcotics law, the antinarcotics struggle 
in the country has been characterized by its isolated efforts 
and meager results. 
  At the end of the 1970's, cultivated coca production did not 
surpass 30,000 hectares. Last year it surpassed 150,000 
hectares, according to the Ofecod [Executive Office for Drug 
Control], which is under the jurisdiction of the Interior 
Ministry. Some less conservative statistics suggest the total 
is about 300,000 hectares. 
  U.S. sources have stated that from 1978 to 1993, drug 
trafficking activities which were previously concentrated in the 
Upper Huallaga Valley expanded at the national level. Some 
200,000 families now farm coca and manufacture cocaine paste. 
Drug-related activities generate an income of about $2 billion 
per year within the Peruvian economy. 
  Many experts believe the failure of the antidrug struggle 
follows the lack of an antidrug strategy and the absence of an 
organization to plan, coordinate, and implement it. 
  The national drug prevention and drug control plan seeks to 
resolve one of the most vulnerable points of the antidrug 
struggle in the country by establishing an organization to 
centralize all government efforts in this field. 
  The General Law on Drugs foresaw in 1978 the need to 
establish an organization to draft a drug control policy, to 
implement it and to coordinate all the actions to be developed. 
  Law No. 22095 established the Multi-Sectorial Drug Control 
Committee (Comucod) [Comite Multisectorial de Control de 
Drogas], an organization to approve the government's antidrug 
policy; and the Ofecod, an executive and coordinating 
organization. Under the law, Comucod was to comprise six 
cabinet members and an alternate from the Supreme Court. The 
truth is that Comucod did not fulfill the duties with which it 
was entrusted by law and never really worked. 
  Ofecod came under the jurisdiction of the Interior Ministry. 
It was to have controlled drugs, and implemented and 
coordinated government actions. As it turned out, Ofecod 
handled administrative functions of disposing of the goods 
seized by the police during antidrug operations and ignored the 
other duties with which it was entrusted by law. 
  Experts believe neither of these organizations completely 
fulfilled its duties. This, undoubtedly, directly influenced 
the expansion of coca farming and trafficking at the national 
level. 
  The lack of leadership, and the dilution and 
ineffectiveness of government actions in the antidrug struggle, 
became obvious in the early 1980's. 
  The main institutions involved in the drug control program 
at 
the time were: the National Coca Enterprise (Enaco); the Upper 
Huallaga Coca Control and Reduction Agency (Corah); and the 
Upper Huallaga Development Program (Peah). 
  Enaco was the government organization responsible for the 
monopoly, legal marketing, and industrialization of coca. In 
fact, it only captured an insignificant part of Peru's coca 
harvest which was mainly being grown for drug traffickers. 
  Corah, which was entrusted with coca eradication programs in 
the area, eliminated several hundred thousand hectares of coca 
in the Upper Huallaga region but paradoxically the valley became 
the main coca producing region in the world. 
  Peah, which was responsible for promoting alternative 
farming 
programs in coca producing regions, yielded insufficient results 
and enjoyed little support among coca farmers. 
  Some experts said the failure of these government 
organizations to control coca farming and trafficking lies in 
the fact that trafficking is merely considered a criminal 
activity that must be disciplined with police repression and 
severe legal punishments. 
  For a long time the antinarcotics struggle was only based on 
repressive actions. The police were the main organization 
entrusted with conducting these repressive actions through its 
diverse specialized units -- among them the Mobile Rural Patrol 
Unit (Umopar), which was involved in the compulsory eradication 
of thousands of hectares of coca; the former Drug Police 
Division (Dipog); the Illicit Drug Traffic Investigative 
Division (Dintid); the Antidrug Division (Dirandro), which later 
became the Antidrug Division (Dinandro). 
  Even today repressive actions are still prevalent. The 
number of actions has risen since July 1992 when the government 
established the Internal Operations Front Command (COFI), which 
falls under the jurisdiction of the Armed Forces. This is the 
top organization, responsible for the planning, implementation, 
and control of the struggle against drugs and terrorism. 
  In the last few years, in addition to repression, the 
authorities have introduced the strategy of alternative 
development. This program seeks to replace economies based on 
coca farming with the alternative farming of legal crops and an 
improvement in the standard of life in coca-producing regions. 
  The Peruvian Government has acknowledged the prevalence of 
the economic and social problems that encourage trafficking. It 
paid particular attention to alternative farming but its results 
in practice have been almost nil. Neither the Institute for 
Alternative Development (Idea), nor the Autonomous Authority for 
Alternative Development (Aada) were ever implemented. 
Considering the antidrug draft bill grants "the highest 
priority" to the alternative development program, there are 
great expectations that this time around, this program will 
finally be implemented. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

