<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Signs Special Powers Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Signs Special Powers Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1604025494 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1604025494 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Rayma Rondon from "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Less than 24 hours after congressional approval, 
President Rafael Caldera signed the Special Powers Law. 
  The new law, which grants special powers to the president, 
allowing him to legislate economic and financial issues, will 
become effective on 20 April, when it will be published in the 
official gazette. 
  President Caldera is to discuss in full that same day the 
Special Powers Law during the Council of Ministers meeting. An 
official source has disclosed the Projects Concessions Law [Ley 
de Obras por el Sistema de Concesiones] will be one of the first 
laws up for approval. The executive branch believes this is an 
important law which is expected to stimulate the economy. 
  [Begin recording] [Allan Viergutz, Venezuelan Oil Chamber 
president] We believe the Concessions Law is very convenient. 
We believe there is a need for creative measures that would 
lead to new options that will benefit the country. These 
measures will allow the government to deal more efficiently with 
the fiscal deficit, high interest rates, and the problem of 
unemployment. This law will stimulate the economy. [end 
recording] 
  It was learned the executive branch, during the 30-day 
period 
the Special Powers Law allows, is prepared to promulgate all 
decrees established in that law. 

</TEXT>

