<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group Opens Fire on Chiapas Military Checkpoint </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Group Opens Fire on Chiapas Military Checkpoint </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1604035294 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1604035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "ACIR Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] At approximately 0530, a group of unidentified 
individuals opened fire on a military checkpoint located on the 
highway from Tuxtla Gutierrez to Chicoasen Dam in Chiapas State. 
The attack lasted approximately 50 minutes. As a result, one 
Mexican Army communications sergeant was wounded and died a few 
hours later at a hospital. This is all that happened in that 
isolated incident. 
  Miguel Angel Godinez Bravo, Seventh Military Region 
commander, explained on behalf of the National Defense 
Secretariat that there is no relation between this incident and 
the Zapatist National Liberation Army [EZLN]. We must also 
point out that at 0600, two Bell combat helicopters and a 
Pilatus Air Force airplane overflew La Chacona Mountain, 
strafing different areas in an attempt to locate the 
perpetrators of the attack. Chiapas Attorney General Arturo 
Becerra Martinez ruled out any connection between this morning's 
clash in Tuxtla Gutierrez and the EZLN. 
  [Begin Becerra recording] So far, we do not know the motive 
or name of the assailants. Until now nothing indicates the EZLN 
is linked to the attack. Should we obtain further information, 
the Attorney General's Office will pass it along to you later. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

