<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1404221594 </F>
<F P=103> PY1404221594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 14 April: 
  The Economic Research Institute Foundation, Fipe, has stated 
that the March Consumer Price Index, IPC, totalled 41.9 percent, 
almost 4 percent up on February. The Brazilian Institute of 
Geography and Statistics for the same period, however, showed 
the IPC totalled 42.7 percent, some 1.76 percent down on 
February. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 8 Apr 
94 p B3) 
  It has been reported that the British businessmen 
accompanying Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd on his visit to 
Brazil have meet with National Iron and Steel Company, CSN, 
board members because they want to participate in the company's 
investment plan. The 6-year CSN plan contemplates investments 
totalling $950 million, $180 million of which have to be made in 
1994. These resources will be used to reduce industrial costs, 
improve quality and productivity, and implement environmental 
control measures. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 7 
Apr 94 p 5) 
  A drop in the net amount of dollars entering the country in 
March caused the Brazilian exchange balance to drop to $1.7 
billion. This is the lowest since September, when it fell to 
$380 billion. Since October, the balance has been surpassing 
$2.5 billion. This is not bad news to the Central Bank which 
has already been controlling the entry of dollars into the 
country to control inflation. (Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in 
Portuguese 8 Apr 94 Section 2 p 1) 
  The number of construction companies that have gone bankrupt 
in Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo in March increased by 43.4 
percent. In November 34 companies went bankrupt, this dropped 
to 22 in December, to 18 in January, and then rose to 23 in 
February. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 8 Apr 94 p 
31) 
  The Goods and Services Movement Tax collection in Sao Paulo 
in March rose by 11.2 percent and totalled $701.5 million. 
Between January and March the Sao Paulo treasury collected 
$1.904 billion in taxes. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 8 Apr 94 p 3) 
  Brazilian exports in January and February decreased from 
$3.1 
billion and $3.5 billion, respectively, during the same period 
in 1993 to $2.75 billion and $2.78 billion, respectively. Semi- 
manufactured product exports in February dropped by 24.81 
percent and shoe exports by 1.17 percent, although coffee 
exports increased by 78.91 percent and orange juice by 65.78 
percent. In the same month, Brazil exported $616.22 million to 
the United States, still its largest trade partner, and $280.2 
to Argentina its second largest trade partner. (Sao Paulo GAZETA 
MERCANTIL in Portuguese 8 Apr 94 p 5) 
  The Brazilian agro-industry grew 2.1 percent in 1993. The 
largest growth was registered in Rio Grande do Sul State, 6.6 
percent, followed by Sao Paulo, 6.5 percent. This positive 
performance is a result of a 3-percent increase in agricultural 
production; soy bean byproducts increased by 4.9 percent; coffee 
byproducts by 7.6 percent; orange byproducts by 19.6 percent; 
and grape byproducts by 19.5 percent. Cacao-bean, wheat, and 
sugar cane production, however, decreased, as did cattle raising 
activities, which dropped by 3.2 percent. (Sao Paulo GAZETA 
MERCANTIL in Portuguese 8 Apr 94 p 17) 
  Brazilian car-manufacturers produced in March the largest 
number of cars in the sector's history. Although the 
car-manufacturing sector had planned to manufacture 1.5 million 
cars by 1995, the number of cars manufactured in the last 12 
months already totals 1,481,000. Another record refers to car 
sales in the domestic market in March when 113,517 cars were 
sold. In 1993, 23 percent of the cars manufactured in the 
country were exported. From January to March this number 
increased by 29.8 percent and 79,711 cars have already been 
exported, 70 percent of them to Argentina. Tractors and 
agricultural equipment manufacture increased by 57 percent from 
January to March and 70.4 percent more of these were sold on the 
domestic market. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
8 Apr 94 p B8) 
  The February unemployment rate totalled 5.37 percent. 
Compared to January, the rate decreased by 0.17 percent. 
(Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 2200 GMT 8 Apr 94) 
  The Getulio Vargas Foundation has reported that the General 
Price Index increased by 44.8 percent in March. The accumulated 
increases since January total 173.8 percent and the increase 
accumulated in the last 12 months totals 3,421 percent. A poll 
by the Interunion Department for Statistics and Socioeconomic 
Studies on the price of basic foodstuff indicates that in March 
these prices increased above the Real Value Unit, URV, in 14 
state capitals. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 8 
Apr 94 p 3) 
  It has been reported that foreign investments on the Sao 
Paulo stock market dropped in March from the 22 percent 
registered in February -- when share movements totalled 
$95,410,000 -- to 20.6 percent. The movement in March totalled 
$62,100,000 million. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 8 
Apr 94 p 20) 
  The Sao Paulo Gas Company has reported that natural gas 
consumption in Sao Paulo State during the months of January and 
February increased by 24.6 percent compared to the same period 
in 1993 in view of the increasing number of industrial 
consumers. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 9 Apr 94 p 
18) 
  It has been reported that fuel prices will rise 18.47 
percent 
countrywide at midnight on 12 April. One liter of gasoline will 
now cost 594,00 real cruzeiros. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO 
in Portuguese 12 Apr 94 p B1) 
  Some of the main national banks will begin to convert a 
larger number of their operations into URV on 12 April. 
Interest rates on those operations will range from 2 percent to 
5 percent over the URV variations. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO 
PAULO in Portuguese 12 Apr 94 pp A1, B1) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

