<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Raul Castro: Civilians Allowed To Leave </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Raul Castro: Civilians Allowed To Leave </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1804122994 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1804122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Army General Raul Castro has warned that if the 
United States unleashes a war against Cuba, no matter under what 
pretext, Cuba would wage a no-holds barred fight against the 
enemy in every corner of the nation where they may be. The 
Guantanamo Naval Base would, of course, be no exception, because 
in the region surrounding it, we have everything necessary to 
neutralize that U.S. enclave. Raul added that in that case, and 
as long as the aggression does not originate from that base and 
the lapsed time is not used to reinforce the base, Cuba is 
willing to allow the time necessary to evacuate civilians from 
the base, primarily the spouses and children of the personnel of 
the U.S. naval base. 
  In the ceremony held in Guantanamo to observe Militiamen's 
Day and the 33d anniversary of the proclamation of the socialist 
nature of the Revolution, Raul stressed that our historic legacy 
is to fight fiercely for the independence of the fatherland, 
under highly disadvantageous conditions, against the enemy; to 
take their weapons; respect prisoners of war; and help injured 
prisoners. After stressing that our people feel admiration and 
gratitude toward their brave sons, the members of the border 
guard troops unit, Raul pointed out that the Revolutionary Armed 
Forces are proud of the courage, dedication, and discipline of 
this unit deployed on the front line. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

