<H3> <TI>   Colombian Official Sees Improved Relations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Colombian Official Sees Improved Relations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1504194794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1504194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Colombian Deputy Foreign Minister Andelfo Garcia, 
who is heading the Colombian delegation to the joint 
Cuban-Colombian commission, has stated that diplomatic relations 
between Cuba and Colombia have been reestablished in order to 
preserve and develop them. This is the first bilateral meeting 
since Cuba and Colombia reestablished diplomatic relations and 
according to Garcia there were no difficulties in reaching 
agreements in the spheres of education, culture, sports, 
tourism, and science. 
  [Begin Garcia recording] There were no problems in moving 
forward in all these spheres. The primary difficulty is the 
reestablishment of regular channels so that these relations can 
flow freely. It is usually up to the governments to open such 
channels and allow such relations to be established by 
initiatives on the part of the two sides. That step has already 
been taken. [end recording] 
  Garcia also said that relations between the two countries 
have been strengthened in a very short period of time. 
  [Begin Garcia recording] After the visits to Bogota of 
Foreign Minister Robaina and Carlos Lage, vice minister of the 
Council of State, relations have been boosted. What we are doing 
is merely the continuation of those efforts, made at the 
presidential level through the meeting between President Castro 
and President Gaviria in Cartagena and later through the visits 
of Foreign Minister Robaina and Vice President Lage -- and now 
we are meeting in this joint commission. [end recording] 
  The conversations of the joint Cuban-Colombian commission 
are 
to continue in October 1994 and April 1995 in Santa Fe de Bogota. 

</TEXT>

