<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Labor Party Endorses Cardoso Candidacy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Labor Party Endorses Cardoso Candidacy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1404143394 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
13 Apr 94 p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY1404143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Brazilian Labor Party [PTB] has joined a group 
of political parties that is seeking to form a front to back the 
presidential candidacy of former Finance Minister Fernando 
Henrique Cardoso. Following the withdrawal of Senator Jose 
Andrade Vieira's candidacy, the PTB is joining the coalition 
sponsored by the PSDB [Brazilian Social Democracy Party], which 
aims to promote Cardoso's election. In addition to the PTB, 
with which an agreement was concluded yesterday, the PSDB is 
already counting in practice on the support of the PFL [Liberal 
Front Party] and the PP [Popular Party]. 
  The consolidation of this big front will require, however, 
further political negotiations. Andrade Vieira was offered the 
Labor Ministry, but he has not yet accepted. PP President 
Alvaro Dias said that the PP "will support Cardoso only if the 
alliance does not collide with the interests of PP candidates 
for state governors." 
  The PSDB is facing a growing internal opposition to an 
alliance with the PFL. Senator Mario Covas, PSDB candidate for 
governor of Sao Paulo State, has again criticized the proposal 
to nominate a PFL member as Cardoso's running mate. Some PSDB 
mayors -- such as Lidice da Mata of Salvador and Paulo Hartung 
of Vitoria, among others -- have conveyed their heightened 
opposition to the PSDB leaders themselves by bringing into focus 
some regional political problems they characterize as 
insurmountable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

