<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Health Official Resigns in `Bribery Scandal' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Health Official Resigns in `Bribery Scandal' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1804131594 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 16 
Apr 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PY1804131594 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] (DYN-NA) -- Matilde Menendez, who resigned Tuesday 
from her seat on the newly-elected Constituent Assembly, stepped 
down as leader of the PAMI pensioners' health scheme yesterday. 
Meanwhile President Carlos Menem announced that she would be 
replaced by power workers' union leader Carlos Alderete. 
  Menendez has been under fire since a bribery scandal 
involving PAMI erupted late February when it was said that the 
organization had been demanding kickbacks from clinics hired to 
carry out medical work. 
  The initial complaint, filed by Frente Grande city 
councillor 
Anibal Ibarra, pointed the finger directly at Menendez for being 
personally responsible for the financial irregularities. That 
in turn led to a host of accusations against her in the 
politically sensitive moment of an electoral campaign. 
  Many observers said her position on the list of Justicialist 
candidates for election to the Constituent Assembly was a prime 
reason for the Peronist failure in the Federal Capital last 
Sunday. 
  However this latest development failed to placate Ibarra who 
said last night that Menendez should have "been forced to go 
long ago" and that the government was guilty of "keeping in 
office those who have been found guilty of corruption." He 
added that if the government had performed better in the 
elections Menendez would still be in office. 
  Meanwhile Alderete told reporters that he would work to 
stamp 
out "all types of corruption and neutralize any cases...if it 
turns out that there are any." 

</TEXT>

