<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Figures Released on Antidrug Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Figures Released on Antidrug Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1404222794 Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p A3 </F>
<F P=103> PY1404222794 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL PERUANO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The government policy in the struggle against 
illegal drug trafficking has allowed the Armed Forces and the 
National Police, which are operating under a single command, to 
seize 28,782 kg of drugs such as cocaine base, cocaine 
hydrochloride, and marijuana in a little more than three years. 
During that period these forces captured 12,975 drug traffickers 
and confiscated 415,000 kg of precursors used by the mafia 
"firms" to make drugs. 
  According to Executive Agency for Drug Control (Ofecod) 
statistics, 3,108 drug addicts were arrested nationwide in 1993. 
  Ofecod also reported that in 1991, drug seizures reached 
5,859 kg. In 1992 the amount was 8,800 kg, which included 8,341 
kg of cocaine base, 231.402 kg of cocaine hydrochloride, and 
227.038 kg of marijuana. 
  In 1993, antidrug operations seized 9,461.511 kg of drugs, 
including 8,586.757 kg of cocaine base, 436.727 kg of cocaine 
hydrochloride, and 437.762 kg of marijuana. 
  From January to 24 March 1994, drug seizures reached 
4,532.675 kg of cocaine base, 18.832 kg of cocaine 
hydrochloride, and 110.051 kg of marijuana. 
  The number of drug traffickers arrested in 1991 was 3,664, 
4,195 in 1992, and 5,022 in 1993. In the first three months of 
this year, 94 drug traffickers were arrested. 
  The police operations also allowed the seizure of 105,527 kg 
of precursors in 1991, 185,895 kg in 1992, and 90,288 kg in 
1993, and 33,323 kg in the first three months of this year. 
  According to estimates by the Interior Ministry and the 
Dinandro [National Antidrug Division], the antidrug forces 
confiscated properties, furniture, equipment, and money worth 
about $51.65 million from the "firms" in 1993. 
  The goods include 41 properties in Lima and the provinces 
and 
115 vehicles including cars, trucks, small airplanes, 
speedboats, and motorcycles. 
  Dinandro also reported that 1993 operations against drug 
traffickers in the Upper Huallaga led to the destruction of 41 
labs for processing drugs and 28 maceration pits. 
  From 1 January to 10 March 1994, the police destroyed 12 
labs 
and 11 maceration pits for making cocaine base. It should be 
pointed out that the largest amount of maceration pits, 315, 
were destroyed in 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10863 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat075_r_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Unequipped To Fly at Night Against Traffickers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Unequipped To Fly at Night Against Traffickers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1804212794 Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 5 Apr 94 pp A6, A7 </F>
<F P=103> PY1804212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL PERUANO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] EL PERUANO was able to establish that the struggle 
against drug trafficking in the Upper Huallaga could be more 
effective if the helicopters the Air Police use in the thick 
jungle areas were equipped to fly at night. 
  This is because of the new tactic used by Colombian drug 
traffickers who land their modern aircraft at night, taking 
advantage of the fact that police aircraft do not have night 
vision devices to detect them and react immediately. 
  An Air Police member commented: "When we started our 
antinarcotic operations in the Upper Huallaga we struck hard 
blows against drug trafficking but all these operations were 
carried out in the daytime. Now the Colombian traffickers carry 
out their operations at night, which complicates matters for us." 
  In addition to limited operational capacity are the 
helicopters' years of service. In the 60's, the UH-1 
helicopters played an important role in the Vietnam war due to 
their great maneuverability and their capacity to escape unhurt 
from the most incredible war situations. 
  However, 30 years later, it can be said that the UH-1 
helicopters have completed their operational cycle. Therefore, 
those operating in the Upper Huallaga must be replaced. 
Accidents have occurred, but the Peruvian police pilots' skill 
has prevented greater disgraces. 
  Another member of the force said: "We need training to 
operate at night with night vision devices, because this would 
make our work more effective. If we had this our actions would 
certainly seriously wound this illegal trade." 
  This policeman has every right to say what he said because 
the information supplied by the silent DEA aircraft, which 
operates with its turbines off in the middle of the night in the 
jungle, cannot be used by the Peruvian pilots because their 
aircraft only fly during the day. 
  Although this has by no means affected police pilots' 
morale, 
neither can it be said that their effectiveness is minimal. 
Facts prove it: The results would be much more significant if 
only they were to operate under other conditions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10864 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat075_r_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Colombians Use New Drug Shipping Center </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Colombians Use New Drug Shipping Center </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1804224594 Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p A13 </F>
<F P=103> PY1804224594 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EL COMERCIO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "special correspondent" Jose Antonio Indacochea </F>
Alvarez] 
  [Text] Puerto Maldonado -- Since mid-1993, Peruvian and 
foreign drug traffickers have chosen Puerto Maldonado as the 
shipping center and exit point for drugs produced in Peru in 
their attempt to dodge the cordon established by the security 
forces in the traditional cocaine production areas. 
  This was proved by three operations carried out by the armed 
and police forces during the past five weeks, during which the 
largest amounts of drugs were seized. 
  A total of 3.5 metric tons of washed cocaine base paste were 
seized on 26 February at Boca Manu airport and more than 1 
metric ton of cocaine base paste on 24 and 26 March at an 
airstrip in Inapari, capital of Tahuamani Province. 
  In every case the cocaine was ready to be loaded on an 
aircraft bound for Colombia, where it was going to be made into 
cocaine hydrochloride that would then be sold in the United 
States and Europe. 
  It was disclosed that the drugs seized in Boca Manu belonged 
to the "Cachique Rivera firm" and that Colombians were involved. 
  It also was disclosed that the drugs seized during the two 
latest operations at Inapari airstrip and the Santa Rosa de 
Fatima farm (15 km from the Shirimayoc checkpoint on the 
Brazilian border) allowed the breaking up of another "firm" that 
supplied drugs to an organization of Colombian drug traffickers 
headed by an individual identified as "Guido Correa." 
  PNP [Peruvian National Police] General Sixto Gutierrez, head 
of the PNP 10th Region, told an EL COMERCIO correspondent that 
"Guido Correa" lives in Cauca Valley (Colombia), from where he 
directs his organization. 
  In view of the harassment by security forces in Upper 
Huallaga, Ucayali, and Ayacucho (where his aircraft used to land 
to load drugs), he decided to find another place for his 
shipments. 
  For this reason he sent to Peru six members of his 
organization identified as "Andres," "Dario," "Tarzan," 
"Bebito," "Lazo," and "Cucaracha," who clandestinely entered the 
country between 14 and 15 March through the "Palestina Peru" 
area on the border of La Convencion (Cuzco) and Ayacucho. They 
were received there by Peruvian citizen "Caliche," with whom 
they made their first contacts. 
  From there they decided to send to Inapari Colombians Miguel 
Manosalva Contreras, 26, Ruben Dario Arango Santa, 35, and 
Andres Ramirez Piedraita, 32, as well as Brazilian Alsimar 
Marquez Da Silva, to buy drugs. 
  Once in Inapari they contacted "Fernando," who is the 
organization's coordinator and, with "Piston," the main drug 
supplier. 
  Thus they managed to gather an initial amount of 400 kg of 
cocaine base paste, which they shipped to Colombia on 20 March. 
Since they saw that there seemed to be no problems they decided 
to continue operating in Inapari and, what is more, built an 
airstrip on the Santa Rosa de Fatima farm. 
  The Army and the PNP, however, thanks to intelligence work, 
found out about this new organization and carried out an 
operation that allowed them to seize more than 1 metric ton of 
cocaine base paste and arrest 23 drug traffickers. Two 
policemen also are being investigated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10865 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat075_r_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suspected Major Figure in Money Laundering Arrested </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Suspected Major Figure in Money Laundering Arrested </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1804233894 Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 4 Apr 94 p A16 </F>
<F P=103> PY1804233894 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima EXPRESO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] One of the front men for the Peruvian Cachique 
Rivera family, engaged in drug trafficking, was arrested on 2 
April in the capital after the Antidrug Division (Dinandro) 
exhaustively investigated an accounting office involved in 
"laundering" money obtained from drug trafficking, according to 
Peruvian National Police [PNP] sources. 
  As is known, the Cachique Rivera brothers belong to one of 
the most important "firms" that supplies drugs to the Colombian 
Cali cartel. According to information obtained by Dinandro, 
they have become the drug trafficking leaders in Peru after the 
arrest of Demetrio Limonier Chavez Penaherrera, aka Vaticano. 
  The alleged owner of the "enterprise," whose identity was 
not 
disclosed, was arrested when he was driving a luxurious metal 
blue Toyota Tercel vehicle, license number DO-3801, in a capital 
neighborhood. According to the source, Dinandro uncovered the 
front man after exhaustively and patiently investigating an 
accounting office in Lima. 
  Despite the secrecy in the case, it was leaked that 
Dinandro's Finance Division, with the technical support of 
auditors, established that the financial movements did not match 
the activities carried out by this "front" enterprise. 
  The source added that after checking the relationship 
between 
the arrested individual and the Cachique Rivera drug trafficking 
family, personnel from that "enterprise" were exhaustively 
investigated. 
  Dinandro thus carried out the successful operation on 2 
April 
when it was proved that the Cachique Rivera's front man was 
involved in "laundering: drug money. 
  It is known that Dinandro Chief General Walter Taboada Milla 
has ordered that investigations into the case continue. 
  Taboada said the Cachique Rivera gang is formed by four 
brothers from Tingo Maria -- Abelardo, aka Teniente; Adolfo, aka 
Alferez; Segundo, aka Capitan; and Nicolas, aka Mayor. 
  According to the source, the Cachique Rivera family is 
headed 
by Abelardo, aka Teniente, the cruelest of the brothers, who -- 
according to the police -- heads the operations of the "firm" 
from Colombia. Segundo, aka Capitan, is in charge of running 
the "business" in the jungle. The other two, according to the 
source, are in charge of collecting the money from drug 
trafficking. 
  Taboada said the arrest of these criminals is a matter of 
days. Peruvian and Colombian authorities are continuously 
exchanging information to find the "narcos." 
  He ended by stating: "We are following them closely. They 
are constantly going to Colombia. We hope to arrest them in a 
few days." 
  The sister in the Cachique Rivera family, Margarita, 30, was 
arrested on 20 March in Lima on an arrest warrant issued by the 
Lima court on charges of drug trafficking. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

