<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-076 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Public Transportation Fares Rise Over Fuel Costs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Public Transportation Fares Rise Over Fuel Costs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1904215894 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1600 
GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1904215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Within a week, the fares for public 
transportation between Port-au-Prince and the outlying 
neighborhoods have gone sky-high. This increase in the cost of 
transport is the direct consequence of the increasing price of 
fuel. Jean-Max Blanc filed a report: 
  [Begin Blanc recording, in Creole] In the last week, the 
cost 
of public transportation has increased in the Haitian capital. A 
gallon of gasoline, which was $20 last week, cost $26 on 18 
April on Boulevard La Saline. The retailers are asking $28 for 
this same gallon of gasoline. A gallon of gas oil costs slightly 
less, $24 in La Saline. Public drivers report that they pay $26 
to $27 for it. 
  Therefore, two gourdes was suddenly added to the regular 
taxi 
fare. There are two kinds of drivers assuring transportation 
between Bourdon and Petionville, Petionville and Delmas, 
Port-au-Prince Cite Soleil and Port-au-Prince-Airport; 
Port-au-Prince and Carrefour. To go from Port-au-Prince to 
Carrefour is seven gourdes; the same with Petionville to Delmas; 
and Petionville to Christ-Roi. 
  The first category of drivers are those who do not demand 
seven gourdes from the passengers. According to them, the price 
still remains at five gourdes. The second category demands seven 
gourdes from the passengers. Those drivers explain that the high 
cost of gasoline causes them to increase the fares. [passage 
omitted] 
  For the other routes, such as for the buses to the airport, 
the cost is five gourdes instead of the 3.5 gourdes it was last 
week. The small buses going from Delmas to downtown cost the 
same as those going to Cite Soleil or other neighborhoods. 
However, the sector that seems to be most affected by the 
increase in the cost of public transportation is the students. 
Not only are buses scarce, but the fares are too high, according 
to a student who worries for the future of students in Haiti. 
[passage omitted] 
  Within a few months, the fare for public transportation has 
tripled. It is not impossible that in two months a parent will 
have to give 30 gourdes [$6] to his child for public 
transportation. 
  Meanwhile, factory workers are also facing misfortune. The 
fare they pay for transport is almost equal to the money they 
earn in a day. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10905 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat076_c_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-076 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2004014694 </F>
<F P=103> PA2004014694 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Mexican economic developments monitored through 19 
April. 
  In the past three years, revenues earned by the 
privatization 
of nonstrategic public organizations totaled $21.8 billion 
pesos, the equivalent of 8.88 percent of international reserves. 
Foreign investment for the past four years totaled 77.7 percent 
of the international resources the country obtained. (Mexico 
City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 12 Apr 94 p 3A) 
  The Chiapas government spent approximately 30 million pesos 
in the first quarter of 1994 to buy 10,000 hectares of arable 
land from ranchers and small landholders in an attempt to 
alleviate the conflicts prompted by the excessive demand for 
land. (Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 12 Apr 94 p 3) 
  The flow of foreign investment in Mexico in March was 50 
percent less than the investment levels obtained in January and 
February, months during which investment totaled approximately 
$1 billion. According to officials of the Commerce and 
Industrial Development Secretariat, this decline resulted from 
recent political events. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 13 
Apr 94 p 17) 
  Mexico signed two credit agreements with the international 
financial community on 11 April. The first agreement, totaling 
$30 million, was signed with the Spanish Government; the second 
one, for $169 million, was signed with the Inter-American 
Development Bank. The loans will be assigned to infrastructure 
and education projects. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 13 Apr 
94 p 18) 
  According to Alberto Marin, Northern Chiapas Cattle Union 
president, the livestock sector has suffered a loss of 
approximately 300 million pesos, particularly in such areas as 
the highlands, the jungle, and the north, as a result of 
multiple peasant invasions. Marin has said the government's 
buying of lands has prompted the invasions to continue. (Mexico 
City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 13 Apr 94 p 9) 
  The Foreign Trade Secretariat has revealed that $5 billion 
were reportedly invested in Mexico during the first quarter of 
1994. This amount is a 150-percent increase over foreign 
investment earned during the same period in 1993. (Mexico City 
NOTIMEX in Spanish 1453 GMT 13 Apr 94) 
  The National Bank of Mexico-Accival Financial Group has said 
in order to achieve the expected level of economic growth and 
employ the available labor force, Mexico will need at least $25 
billion in foreign aid in 1994 due to an insufficient rate of 
savings, which ranks below 10 percent. The bank's experts have 
said in the past two years more than 70 percent of foreign 
investment was in stocks. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 
14 Apr 94 p 7) 
  Mexican and Taiwanese businessmen have earmarked $7.5 
million 
to start a pioneering industrial project in Fresnillo, 
Zacatecas, where shoes will be made for export to the United 
States and Canada. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2043 GMT 15 
Apr 94) 
  The National Foreign Trade Bank has placed on the 
international markets the lowest-priced issue of bonds in the 
past 12 years for the amount of $250 million. Foreign 
investors' purchase of these bonds will inject security and 
stability into the Mexican economy. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in 
Spanish 15 Apr 94 p 16) 
  Mexico and New Zealand have signed an agreement to 
strengthen 
ties in trade and investment and to grant the agricultural 
sector easier access to both countries' markets. (Mexico City 
EL FINANCIERO in Spanish 15 Apr 94 p 21) 
  An EL FINANCIERO study indicates interest payments on the 
foreign debt in the private sector will increase by $100 million 
in addition to the estimated $2.1-billion debt pending for 1994. 
This increase results from a rise in international interest 
rates and an 8.5-percent devaluation of the peso vis-a-vis the 
U.S. dollar in recent weeks. Data provided by the Bank of 
Mexico, the Mexican Stock Market, and local and foreign experts 
show the leading Mexican companies, total of 36, incurred 
substantial foreign debts. (Mexico City EL FINANCIERO in 
Spanish 15 Apr 94 pp 1, 4, 5) 
  The Finance Secretariat has said Mexican exports during 
February reached $4.4 billion, a 17.4-percent increase compared 
with February 1993. According to a Finance Secretariat 
communique, nonpetroleum exports increased by 23.7 percent. 
(Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1516 GMT 16 Apr 94) 
  High-ranking government officials have confirmed that thus 
far, $980.7 million from the Contingency Fund have been 
allocated to support the Mexican peso in the exchange market. 
The Finance Secretariat has said the $6 billion granted by the 
United States to counter any pressure to devalue the peso are 
still available. (Mexico City UNOMASUNO in Spanish 18 Apr 94 p 
16) 
  According to the Bank of Mexico, its foreign indebtedness 
increased by 115 percent from 1989 to this date and currently 
totals approximately $21 billion. In addition, banks' foreign 
indebtedness represents 51.2 percent of the total debt 
contracted by the public sector abroad and equals 17.6 percent 
of Mexico's total foreign indebtedness. (Mexico City LA JORNADA 
in Spanish 18 Apr pp 64, 54) 
  Mexican Petroleum has earned $482 million in revenues for 
Mexico by selling an average of 1.3 million barrels of crude per 
day to its clients in America, Europe, and Asia. The United 
States, 72.3 percent, Spain, 14.1 percent, and Asia, 14.4 
percent, were Mexico's leading clients during January. (Mexico 
City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0119 GMT 19 Apr 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

