<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1904192794 </F>
<F P=103> PA1904192794 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on El Salvadoran economic developments monitored through 
19 April. 
  In 1993, the Inter-American Development Bank, IDB, approved 
$109 million in loans to El Salvador. According to an official 
spokesperson, this money was used for social projects and 
infrastructure plans coordinated by various government offices. 
(San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU in Spanish 1800 GMT 14 Apr 94) 
  The Central Bank has reported that in the first three months 
of 1994 Salvadoran families received $223.2 million from family 
members living abroad. According to the bank, the Salvadoran 
economy was kept afloat throughout the civil war years by money 
Salvadorans living abroad sent their family members. (Paris AFP 
in Spanish 1903 GMT 18 Apr 94) 
  The local press has reported that Japan has approved a $99 
million loan to El Salvador to rebuild bridges destroyed during 
the 12 years of civil war. (Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2020 
GMT 18 Apr 94) 

</TEXT>

