<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Urge Review of Military Treaty With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials Urge Review of Military Treaty With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Armed Forces Chief Terms Treaty `Obsolete' </H4>

<F P=102> PA1904182794 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1614 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1904182794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tegucigalpa, 19 Apr (DPA) -- General Luis Alonso 
Discua, commander-in-chief of the Honduran Armed Forces, 
confirmed today that the Armed Forces want to break the military 
assistance treaty with the United States because they consider 
it obsolete and, according to military leaders, it does not 
benefit the country. 
  Gen. Discua said the Armed Forces will attempt to submit the 
treaty for review by the Honduran Congress Defense Committee. 
  The United States signed a military assistance treaty with 
Honduras in 1954 and, according to Discua, it currently benefits 
the United States. 
  Discua referred specifically to the U.S. military base at 
Palmerola in the central department (province) of Comayagua, 
noting that it is important to examine whether it is appropriate 
to keep the base open in Honduras. 
  U.S. assistance to Honduras has been reduced drastically in 
the past year, and according to Discua, U.S. assistance is 
conditional upon various situations and even includes sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

